  "editorial": {
    "title": "Efficient Removal of Duplicates from Sorted Doubly Linked List",
    "intuition": "The problem can be solved efficiently by traversing the linked list once and skipping nodes with duplicate values. The key observation is that since the list is sorted, duplicates will be adjacent.",
    "bruteForce": "A brute force approach would involve comparing each node's value with all previous nodes to check for duplicates, resulting in a time complexity of O(n^2). This is inefficient for large lists.",
    "betterSolution": "Instead of comparing with all previous nodes, we can simply keep track of the previous node's value and skip inserting a new node if its value is the same as the previous one.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal solution involves a single pass through the list, maintaining a reference to the previous node and the head of the new list. This approach has a known time complexity of O(n) and space complexity of O(n).",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The correctness can be proven by induction. The base case is when the list is empty or contains a single node, which is inherently duplicate-free. For the inductive step, assuming the first k nodes are correctly processed without duplicates, adding the (k+1)th node will only require checking if it's different from the kth node. If it is, it's added; if not, it's skipped, maintaining the invariant of no duplicates.",
    "dryRun": "A dry run with a sample input, such as 5 1 1 2 3 3, helps verify the approach. The expected output should be 1 2 3, which matches the manually computed result.",
